\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 A very ancient (and very current!) form of human autocosmics: the attribution of causality to unknown or unrelated forces through cultural naivety or norms.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93False causality is the basis for much superstition.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93In the past gave order to a chaotic and unpredictable world.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Sir James Frazer's 'classic' (Hutton) definition of magic - practices designed to bring spiritual or supernatural forces under the control of human agents. Dealing with systems, complexity, the unknown\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 (Plato) }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Magic is, in fact, everything that absolutely fascinates minds and attract souls by means of words and deeds\u8230\'85 they are difficult for the mind to perceive, and their causes are veiled from the simpleton. That is because it is a divine force associated with advanced reasons for the purpose of understanding it.\u8221\'94 "the world of popular belief and custom... practical remedies for specific problems" \u8220\'93The unknown with the belief, even amongst the superstitious, that there existed credible rules for its control.\u8221\'94}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 Opies say that supersititon have too much weight as a word - could not ask about those}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 . }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Ritual (Hutton) - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "formal, dramatic and unusually stylized action".}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 McClenon - shamanic ritual and placebo effect - actually is a signal to the body that it can survive. Those who are susceptible to placebo did get better.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 p97 - 100 - he talks about cargo cults as e.g. of religion as "intentional stance". "the raw materials of religion".}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 Building on Boyer's work - systems in the human brain in tandem allow proto-religious thoughts. Hypnotism as the placebo effect, hallucinogens and ethnogens (building on McClenon's work).}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "supernormal stimuli" - bigger than life stimuli that we gravitate towards. Characters are examples of these. "a well-designed few" make it through to become solid ideas.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "saturating the human environment with folk psychology"}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 . }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 Religion as instinct, and may actually be better to have a general myth that everybody agrees on (and which we all end up following becausse everybody does) than misunderstanding the actual reason on our own. "better safe than sorry"}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The word has long been used in a derogatory sense to describe what were perceived to be unfounded, credulous or heretical beliefs. Ancient Roman and Greek authors applied it to \u8216\'91uncivilised\u8217\'92 people outside the Classical world. The early Church used it in its campaign against the pagan religions which it ultimately vanquished.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Skinner's work on superstition (i.e. the basal pattern matching) in pigeons. Is a version of autocosmics, of mental simulation, of causality. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "In a species that does represent both itself and other agents to itself, the effect can be multiplied." }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 When we speak about superstition generally, we are often talking about extra-religious or folk beliefs. v. relevant to my story. Anne lives in a time when \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91false\u8217\'92 inferences about the natural world were battling with both organised inferences (I.e. the Bible) and science. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Davies - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 magical activities were no longer considered as technically feasible but rather explicitly fraudulent pretences designed to fool the credulous\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 . (After Witchcraft Act of 1736). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Often called }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93the long 18th century}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 because of the perceived change in social, political and personal identities from 1700 to 1800.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf5\cb4\highlight4  Anne is placed right in the middle. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Intellectually the whole basis for witchcraft and magic was being questioned.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 (In Davies) John Dove \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 foolish artifices\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8230\'85 against mischief merely imaginary\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 very negative, not as benign as now.The concept was a "cultural weapon" against the piopulace. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Superstition could be grouped under \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91popular magic\u8217\'92. Distinguished from \u8216\'91high magic\u8217\'92.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 But still lots of people believed in magic.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Keith Thomas was the first point of academic reference in 70s - said magic \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91declined\u8217\'92 in 18th century. Fits with Enlightenment narrative. De Bleacourt and other recent scholars dispute this. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93It was appropriated as an Enlightenment tool, and added to the arsenal of words used to enforce a self-conscious intellectual and cultural break with the past.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93It is too crude and misleading to portray the Enlightenment as a period of intellectual and social leaps\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93Yet the majority of people across Europe undoubtedly felt exactly the same about witches, and much else besides, whether they lived in the early seventeenth century or the early nineteenth century.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Davies & de Blecourt (BTWT) }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93so-called enlightenment\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 BTWT that it continued for centuries, despite the enlightenment. Brian Hoggard -}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93continuation and survival of witchcraft practices\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93The decline of magic was a slow and long drawn-out affair.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Gap between complex ambivalence of popular culture and the simplistic dichotomy preached by the church in relation to spirits. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 the debrus of many different thoughts.\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 (Thomas). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The line between orthodoxy and heresy [was] extremely thin\u8221\'94}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The opposition between modern academic categories and contemporary indigenous ones.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 The elite and the people often believed the same thing, but there were class-defined manifestations of superstition. Dyer deals with this an awful lot. Davies\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 demographic breakdown of visitors to cunning folk; many rich and educated people.Priests becoming cunning folk. Priests were often cunning-folk (or at least astrologers) - thought that they were helping their parishioners }
