\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 The Anglican Chrich \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93had long given up on trying to suppress popular magic at grassroots level\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93The attempt by the theologicans to wipe out the distinction between black and white witches by branding them both as diabolical never got through to the people to whom these witches ministered\u8221\'94 (thomas). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super\cf6\cb4\highlight4 Witchcraft Act not repealed until 1952 (from Hutton). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Examples from Anne\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s time - witch marks }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93making the world a safer, less hostile place.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4  (Duncan Wilson, guardian article). Just a quick reference to the article on burying stuff in walls and floors, just like Anne does. Dolls cut in half, belt buckles, knives, human skull and cross-bones, a donkey buried under the barn. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Spiritual armory of the house\u8221\'94 As Roberta Harding says - blood was used, aristocracy\u8217\'92s heads, from beheading, were sources of superstitious ingredients. Cultural nature of it - fulfilling a need as healthcare was bad. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Superstitions function as a form of public healthcare\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 "individual christians seeking success and security in their daily lives by their own efforts". Systems are hard - therefore divination is a way to make these decisions. "candidates to press into service as decision aids"}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Cunning folk -}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93provided numerous magical services to assuage the illnesses, fears, misfortunes and desires of the general populace\u8221\'94. "cunning folk seem to have been virtually immune from legal harrassment". \u8220\'93Two hundred years ago the majority of the population\u8230\'85 would have known at least one cunning-man or cunning-woman.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93Individuals who straddled the worlds of both learned and low magic\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93Curing the mad, bad and sad\u8221\'94 - }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 sufferers of their autocosmics, or rather of the world! }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Setting up \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93supernatural protection rackets\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 "rival therapists for the community's affliction". Demons were behind cunning-folk work, they said. }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Familiars (like the Spyrit) - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93the affectionate and intimate relationship often found between the witch/cunning woman and her familiar/fairy\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Belief in fairies was much lesser.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Both familiars and fairies were elieved to possess a range of supernatural powers that were considered capable of affecting almost any aspect of human life\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Parallel to the hobman,}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93living alone\u8230\'85 either alongside humans in their houses\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Characterised superstition. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Substances such as ale or milk were often poured on springs, trees and rocks sacred to fairies, while bowls of bread, milk or water and suchlike were left in the kitchen overnight for the domestic hobman\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Familiars - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93clearly-defined, three-dimensional\u8230\'85 forms, vivid with colour and animated with movement and sound\u8221\'94 - just like computer character!}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93This old hag travelled with a Guinea pig in her breast, which she pretended solved questions\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4  - autocosmic pets.The Devil as a character - a person only experienced through mediation - witch trials, saying his name etc. Belief in \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93brownies\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93liv[ing] alongside humans in theor own houses and farms\u8221\'94, working by night, cannot be controlled, only supplicated by cream and porridge on the hearth. Belief in fairies persisted in Scotland, but waned in England. Changelings, superstitious use of wells, 2nd sight (again in Scotland, p. 87). Marks funereal rituals (and perhaps ghosts and spirit systems) as a tension between inability to remove one's intentional stance to the dead other and needing to remove the physical, possibly diseased physical reminder of them. And that these characters could evolve, free of physical reality, }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cb4\highlight4 Animal forms, not particularly supernatural. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Perhaps because of fear of the unnatural as being outside God, also because animals formed a symbiotic relationship with everyday people. (Wilby) }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The familiar most frequently appeared in animal form, often living in domestic intimacy with the witch.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Consensus - not necessarily belief, but a socially-mandated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91playing\u8217\'92, a magic circle, in many regards. Dyer (BTWT) asserts that from the sufferer\u8217\'92s perspectives, it was an autocosmic maelstrom both informed by their supernatural beliefs and social/familial expectations - the cunning-person allowed \u8216\'91blessed relief\u8217\'92 - a consensual end to the autocosmics. \u8220\'93Genuine respect moderated by doses of cynicism\u8221\'94. This time period was definitely when the magic circle started to actually grow in strength - difference between affirmative ritual and truth.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super\cf6\cb4\highlight4 "R.R Marrett agreed that ritual was essential and belief secondary... emotion rather than reason was the key" (398)}
