\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Dennett: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We can analuse the artifice in religious texts and ceremonies just as we can analuse the artifice in literature in other arts." (154). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 "Design and techniques" of religion, "amalgam of brilliant plays and stratagems". "religion's contrary" - of course, we can draw the same autocosmic arguments about religion. Church people - "unbridgeable gulf between... religion and magic". }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 Evolutionary theory applied to religious beliefs - have survived over time because they seem to work. "folk religions" - pretty much superstitions organise - "vestigial traces" in organised religion. "evolved product of many adjustements". "free-floating rationales" -> "carefully-crafted reasons". Linking it to memes - infectious ideas. Belief is the core differentiation between superstition and religion. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 Talks about the commeasurate evolutionary fitness of language and religion, both to "genetic fitness" and "cultural fitness" - clear benefits, mutualists. In religion, resonance is the ultimate - they will die, not just be bad, if not used.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 folk religion is superstition and organised religion is different - in the previous (according to Dennett) people don't think of themselves as practicing a religion - it is just life. Relgiion is more like art, a bounded space outside of life. Therefore let us think of art more like folk art.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Difficult to separate superstition and religion: both rely on autocosmic simulation: to seek patterns, to mentally simulate, to create complex narrative out of sensory and mental percepts. Brown and Holden - science and magic, to the layman, differ only in idiom. Both rely on character, gods as agents (Dennett). Holy texts provide characters that have resonated for thousands of years - Muhammad, Jesus, the prophets. They are both allegorical and individual. Gods are manifestations of the autocosmic, and our relationship with the world around us.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93magic and religion - \u8220\'93terms notoriously difficult to define\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 For Harding, they are }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93a manifestation of humankind\u8217\'92s longstanding effort to comprehend the elementary principles of good and evil.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93powerful manifestations of our own fears and hopes and dreams. The invention - the finding within of gods represents our reach for the transcendent.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 McCorduck - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93human yearning for the transcendent\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 The.emergence.of.stories.may.have.begun.with.shamanistic.or.early.religious.beliefs.resulting.from.an.expansion.of.the.concept.of.theory.of.mind.(Boyer,.2001)..For.Boyer.(2001),.religious.beliefs. are.theorized.to.stem.from.two.constraints:.a.salience.constraint.and.an.inferential.constraint..The. salience.constraint.stresses.that.the.belief.must.be.conspicuous:.drawing.attention.to.its.novelty,. often.by.breaking.the.laws.of.nature..The.representation.is.circumscribed.to.some.extent.by.the. inferential.constraint:.Inferences.must.be.allowed.regarding.the.intention.of.the.object.or.agent..A. storyteller,.through.an.expansive.theory.of.mind,.could.place.himself.or.herself.in.the.mind.of.an. agent.or.object..For.example,.a.storyteller.could.claim.that.a.river.has.talked.to.her.(salience.constraint),.and.the.fact.that.the.river.spoke.is.a.sign.that.the.hunting.season.will.not.be.fruitful.this.year.(inferential.constraint)..Thus,.the.storyteller,.through.an.expansive.theory.of.mind,.can.bring.mean- ing.to.the.community..This.meaning-making.ability.could.then.be.extended.to.other.contextsIn.the.prehistoric.period,.humans.may.initially.have.attempted.to.understand.phenomena.such.as. fertility.through.stories.ascribing.personality.characteristics.to.unseen.characters..Festinger.(1983). suggested.that.those.who.could.bring.meaning.to.the.community.by.discerning.supernatural.phe- nomena.would.become.the.elite..Perhaps.effective.storytellers,.who.could.create.meaning.by.telling. stories.about.such.subjects.as.gods.in.conflict,.would.have.had.an.advantage.in.prehistoric.society.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 An illusion, but did Calvino think that it was \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93high\u8221\'94 fantasy\u8221\'94?}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 "the believer is called upon personally to paint frescoes crowded with figures on the walls of his mind, starting out from the stimuli that his visual imagination succeeds in extracting from the theological proposition of a laconic verse from the gospels". }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Critics made the links between literature (specifically poetry) and religion/play, particularly religion of individual people, rather than liturgy. (Huizinga).}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Big links between superstition in the time period that I am looking at and religion: many of the grimoires used religious language, particularly Catholic (re. Book of Soyga), \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93relics of old Catholicism\u8221\'94 in popular culture. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Catholicism possessed a fundamental vehicle\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8230\'85 ability to use visual communication.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4  Cunning folk techniques }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93often contained a large component of Christianity\u8221\'94, }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 and }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93the Bible\u8230\'85 [was] regularly treated as a magical object in itself\u8221\'94; \u8220\'93made a show of using the Bible in their consulting rooms\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 . Examples of priests who were cunning folk, or who believed in the power of superstition. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Cunning-folk borrowed from Catholic practices\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93No known case of a cunning person or charmer calling upon a pagan deity\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Clergy were the biggest users and makers of magical books.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Intrinsic Christian content of magic.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 dusty Catholic mysticism\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Examples of what would probably be called \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93aesthetic illusion\u8221\'94 in religion - Boxley Rood - people were complicit in magic circle, not duped or fooled - \u8216\'91pretended\u8217\'92 it was a real miracle, gave donations to the monks. But why did they pretend? Part of their wider autocosmic relationship with the world, \u8220\'93more complicated\u8221\'94 than simply belief or pantomime.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  A}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93theatrical miracle\u8221\'94 (Groeneveld). Criticism tied to \u8220\'93sweeping away of Catholic mysticism\u8221\'94. Stories about it getting down, attacking women, could both worship and be entertained by them. \u8220\'93personal affective responses\u8221\'94. A piece of installation art, just like Yocto.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Groeneveld states that removing and parading the Rood before destruction was designed to decontextualise it, to bring it into the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93harsh light of day\u8221\'94 rather than the theatrical settings of the monastery. The spoilsporting is really interesting here. (Murray) Religious services are designed as narrative bottlenecks, to control people\u8217\'92s exposure to the machinery of the divine - not fraudulent, merely reliant on both sides performing in a certain way, after being given the furniture of the suspension of disbelief. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Bocca Della Verita - a proto-arcade autocosmic machine. (still a massive queue to see it)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Prayers being answered - we are in a performative state of mind to see a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91sign\u8217\'92, or a way. Acheiropoieta - religious images made without human intervention - Turin Shroud, images in toast.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "a certain element of 'make-believe' is operative in all primitive religions... the really important thing is the //mood//."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What becomes of the divintiy when it reveals itself in icons, when it is multiplied in simulacra\u8230\'85 the visible machinery of icons substituted for the pure and intelligble Idea of God?\u8221\'94 - against baudrillard idea - icons and \u8220\'93graven images\u8221\'94 excite the imagination. People were \u8220\'93content to venerate a filigree God\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93already enacting his death and his disappearance in the eipophany of his representations\u8221\'94 - this is a big subject, but I don\u8217\'92t think that God disappears because he is an icon, or into his icons. \u8220\'93But what if God can be sumulated\u8230\'85 can be reduced to the signs that constitute faith? Then the whole system becomes weightless.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Like superstition, religion is an example of autocosmic phenomenon outside of the purely literary or artistic: an interactive parlay with our own minds and the minds of those around us, with a wide magic circle and a powerful narrative and character-led streak; something before which we are not entirely helpless, but which we instead luxuriate ourselves in.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Ah, you realize that magick is something we do to ourselves. But it is more convenient to assume the objective existence of an angel who gives us new knowledge than to allege that our invocation has awakened a supernormal power in ourselves.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4  (Kaczynski, 542)}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aiwass#cite_note-Veale-11"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super\cf6\cb4\highlight4 [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\super\cf6\cb4\highlight4 11. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Dogma is the contradictory heart of human religion. Religion is born and thrives on autocosmics; dogma seeks to control the human imagination and conscious thought. It never works, not completely.}
