\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Even though principles of rationality seem as often violated as followed, we still cling to the notion that human thought should be rational, logical and orderly.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 (Donald Norman). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Reason has not ended our relationship with magic.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 (Davies).}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Even in today\u8217\'92s technologically advanced and scientifically sophisticated society, they continue to be part of the cultural landscape.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 (Roberta Harding). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf3\cb4\highlight4 "fossil traces of animism" in how we treat modern-day things. "treat things as agents with beliefs and desires" (Dennett). "astrology-seekers and numerologists who still inhabit our high-tech Western culture".Links belief in primitive forces to our own beliefs in what we cannot see and touch (atoms etc.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Often confine it to children, and indeed much research has been done on the superstitions of children, most notably the Opies on the work of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93half-beliefs\u8221\'94 of children in the 1950s. (Hickling & Wellman 2001), particularly in how they conduct animism (Turkle, Gjersoe) and have imaginary friends (Gjersoe, Marjorie Taylor). But much research has also been done into how this can extend into adulthood (Gjersoe, Leonards, Connelly, Bloom & Hood, 2009), and how these initial ways of looking at the world are not shrugged off, but change throughout our lives.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Religion is still a mightily powerful force in the world: the power of words, the vividness of its literary characters, the belief in a supernatural influence over the world, the constant autocosmic searching for answers within established frameworks.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Hutton questions whether cunning-craft ever died out - merely metamorphosed into "alternative" therapies of today.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Also still extremely superstitious. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Study in 2009 (Theos) 39% of adults believe in ghosts, 22% believe in reincarnation and 22% believe in astrology.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4  Belief in cunning folk persisted into the twentieth century, and scholars like Hutton believes that there is a continuum with modern day superstitious behaviour, buoyed by scientific progress. Older writers (such as Malinowski) believed that magical thinking and superstition in the modern age is clearly non-Western and \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91savage\u8217\'92 in nature. Not true at all. Even with scientific advancement, our autocosmics are not completely controllable by reason, and the line between \u8216\'91healthy\u8217\'92 and \u8216\'91unhealthy\u8217\'92 autocosmics is very thin}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 .}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4  OCD as an example(), homeopathy(), clean eating(), animism in the elderly with dementia (}{\f3\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Zaitchik and Solomon 2008}{\f3\fs26\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 )}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4  .}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Belief in astrology is still quite high, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "astrology is pervasive in Western society", even amongst science students ().}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4  We still approach much of the world in a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93pre-theoretical\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4  (Ullman), naive manner, creating our own narratives, and culturally-enforced narratives, for the way things are.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  And creating }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 characters is a big part of that! Still use anthropomorphism in our science (names of stars, and the Zodiac). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 "The paranormal [for some] determines the devisions they may make about important events in their lives". }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Legare & Souza (2012) - rituals are a "cognitive paradox". 'simpatias' in Brazil - "intutive causal principles" - time of day, repetition of procedures - just like with the creature! Relate this forward to manuals/grimoires. It *seems" like they should work. And "transcendental influence" (presence of religious iconography - make rituals more effective. The character of ritual, the setting, the context, the techniques used to stimulate the autocosmic (just like character).}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 Even less dramatic than this: at a low level, our brains are geared towards find causal links from seeming correlations, maintaining internal logic when we cannot maintain total external logic, as the world outside is not completely known. This combined with counter-factual thinking (), imagining alternatives to the world as we know it, can have powerful effects on us psychologically and physically, and change our behaviour to maintain those states. Often made worse by stress (Keinan, 1994). The Barnum Effect(), the Placebo Effect (Neil 1980, Van Raalte, Brewer, Nemeroff and Linder 1991), conducting rituals when mourning reduces grief (Norton & Gino, 2013), Simulation Heuristic (Kahneman and Tversky) and how it can go wrong amongst those with clinical anxiety (Raune, Macleod and Holmes 2005) (Nan & her not getting on her tram at the last minute, plane crash survivors who changed flights at the last minute) - and}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  lo}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 ts of research has been done into how rituals before sports can change our performance (Foster & Weigand 2006, Mamassis and Doganis 2003, Damisch, Stoberock and Mussweiler 2010); indeed, in }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93any situation where the outcome is important and uncertain and beyond their control\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 . And even when we do not directly \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91believe\u8217\'92 in the causation at hand, just doing the actions can have positive psychological effects. Within a \u8216\'91magic circle\u8217\'92. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Unnecessary to consciously believe in the superstition.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4 Pareidolia - seeing faces.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The power of positive thinking has been proven to have physiological beenfits, and so, in this sense at least, magic may have worked.\u8221\'94 }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb4\highlight4 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Merely providing a concrete diagnosis of witchcraft could have a beneficial, psychosomatic effect.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb4\highlight4  The same apparatus that we use to enjoy stories, to augment and create characters ourselves, is used out in the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93real\u8221\'94 world. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb4\highlight4 "Each one of us is now forced to do for ourselves what in previous ages was done by family, custom, church, and state - namely, create for ourselves the myths that will let us make some sense of experience."}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb4\highlight4  (May)}
